<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911223-0091</DOCNO><DOCID>911223-0091.</DOCID><HL>   BCCI Enters Guilty Plea   To State Criminal Charges</HL><DATE>12/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BCCI</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)WESTERN U.S. BANKS (BAW)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)</NS><RE>ARABIAN PENINSULA (ARA)CALIFORNIA (CA)DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)EUROPE (EU)LUXEMBOURG (LU)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (TC)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Bank of Credit andamp; Commerce International, asexpected, pleaded guilty to criminal charges in state courtin Manhattan.   The bank's parent, BCCI Holdings (Luxembourg) S.A., andthree other BCCI-related concerns admitted felony counts ofscheming to defraud, grand larceny and money laundering inconnection with drug trafficking. State Judge PeterMcQuinlan, calling the scandal a &quot;world-wide con game,&quot; finedthe companies a total of $10 million.</LP><TEXT>   The guilty plea and fine are part of a settlementannounced last week with state and federal officials in whichBCCI will forfeit all its $550 million in U.S. assets. Aspart of the agreement, the BCCI companies also are expectedto plead guilty in January to a charge of racketeeringconspiracy in federal court in Washington.   Under the settlement, about half of the $550 million willbe put in a fund to cover claims against BCCI in the U.S. Thefund will also be used to provide additional capital to FirstAmerican Bankshares Inc., Washington, and Independence Bankof Encino, Encino, Calif., which had been secretly controlledby BCCI. The other half of the money will be distributed todepositors in other countries who lost money when BCCI wasseized by regulators in several countries on July 5 amidallegations of massive fraud. The alleged fraud is estimatedto have caused billions of dollars in losses.</TEXT></DOC>